From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Yuki Sireneva <sylfn@disroot.org>
Date: Sat, 20 Jun 2026 10:35:38 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] (Fix) setBadgeNumber bug workaround

Qt uses `applicationName` in object path unconditionally without
escaping it, creating object paths like

	/com/canonical/unity/launcherentry/com.example.MyCoolApp

that are invalid according to both Qt and D-Bus spec as they contain
unallowed characters (dots).

Previous code (for qt < 6.6, even though it should have been 6.5)
talked to D-Bus manually and used hashes instead of full name.

I'm unsure whether it is really a Qt bug or I'm just unlucky to have hit
this corner case, because I set applicationName to application id...

diff --git a/Telegram/SourceFiles/platform/linux/main_window_linux.cpp b/Telegram/SourceFiles/platform/linux/main_window_linux.cpp
index 803afb7b59..8d66689711 100644
--- a/Telegram/SourceFiles/platform/linux/main_window_linux.cpp
+++ b/Telegram/SourceFiles/platform/linux/main_window_linux.cpp
@@ -155,9 +155,9 @@ void MainWindow::updateWindowIcon() {
 }
 
 void MainWindow::updateUnityCounter() {
-#if QT_VERSION >= QT_VERSION_CHECK(6, 6, 0)
-	qApp->setBadgeNumber(Core::App().unreadBadge());
-#else // Qt >= 6.6.0
+// #if QT_VERSION >= QT_VERSION_CHECK(6, 6, 0)
+// 	qApp->setBadgeNumber(Core::App().unreadBadge());
+// #else // Qt >= 6.6.0
 	using namespace gi::repository;
 
 	static const auto djbStringHash = [](const std::string &string) {
@@ -198,7 +198,7 @@ void MainWindow::updateUnityCounter() {
 						GLib::Variant::new_boolean(counterSlice))),
 			}),
 		}));
-#endif // Qt < 6.6.0
+// #endif // Qt < 6.6.0
 }
 
